args:
After the party meets a mysterious dragon
called Nyarlathotep in the unsealed library,
an incident there makes them realize the
missing villagers have been transformed into
books. Their investigation takes on a new
urgency as they hurry to save the people.
So this is the Library Obscura, is it?
I can scarce believe such a structure\nwas right under the Halidom's nose.
It's a rather curiously designed edifice.\nIt almost feels as if someone forced it\ninto such a contorted shape.
It's making me dizzy just looking at it.\nI sure hope I don't horf!

Appearances are trivial. Behold, if you
would, these walls positively covered in
books! So many books! Their covers
alone are enough to captivate me!
As was written within the Liber Grimortis,\nthis place is filled with all manner of\nboth taboos and truths!

This is no time to be getting your feathers
ruffled with excitement, Heinwald.
Just hurry up and track down a clue
so we can get on with this.
Ha! As if I simply wander about searching\nthe ground for clu... I say, what's that?
Why do you come hither, O travelers?\nFor beyond this ingang dwell accursed\nopuscules with no purchase in the light.
Speak! Be you unwelcome visitants,\nor yet long-awaited obtruders?

We are Chaos, both atheneum and keeper.
We are the deepening wedge, yet that very
wedge unbound! We are what looks most
grievously upon Our shuttered shelves.
I'm afraid I cannot follow of what\nyou speak, dragon.
Yeah, I'm getting about zero percent\nof what you're going on about.
Comprehension is not the obtention of\nknowledge. If those it falls upon fail to\nregister thus, it is but smoke and oakum.
I think we're going to get along, dragon.
You actually know what he's on about,\nHeinwald?
Essentially, he's saying that the\nignorant can't possibly understand\nthe knowledge he possesses.
One of this type in my life was more than\nenough for me, thanks.
Right then! Let me ask you a question,\nMr. Thesaurus. Are you friend or foe?

You shall find no hedgerow here. No walls.
We are fettered, trapped by quailing wings.
Yet We do not blame the stake, for it
knows naught but the art of binding.
It seems he will not interfere with us,\nat any rate.
Each and every thing this dragon says\nis more bothersome than the last.
I'm just glad he's not our enemy.\n...What is your name, dragon?
Our name is Unbeing. Chaos. The Black.\nOur name is writ in water ephemeral.\nYet once some called Us...Nyarlathotep.

The appellation Nyarlathotep denotes not
ourself entire. It is but a word pulled from
aether to define the indefinable, for we are
not bound by a single sobriquet or form.
Man, even your NAME is a huge pain!
Have you always been in this library?
This place is a ziggurat of the Ancient One,\nfar older yet than your goddess. The tomes\naccrued within are oblations unto It.

We, too, are an offering; a sacrifice that
strives without ceasing to gainstay fate.
Besotted atonement; a ruler absolute;
stitched into the very fabric of Our throne.

It seems this building is dedicated to the
belief and worship of a being other than
the Goddess Ilia—something called
the Ancient One.
Do you think the people of Hethiwood\nalso worshiped this...thing?
It is folly to make conjectures without\nbacking data. But with that being said,\nit IS a deeply interesting coincidence.
All right, dragon! Spill it!\nTell us everything you know!

The truth is distant to those who strain
against it. The moon waxes and wanes
anon while awaiting wealds to germinate
from seed.

For you to seek a grand jewel would
be to pour water into a shattered urn.
You can but obtain the single pebble
before your eyes.

So rather than trying to comprehend a
difficult thing, it would be faster to look
at things that actually lie around us.
That's rather kind advice, actually.
You can't actually FOLLOW what he's\nsaying, right? I mean, you're clearly\njust making it up to seem cool.
While the phrasing may be opaque,\nthe advice itself is quite simple.
So if I understand this, he's suggesting\nwe look for more information in some\nof the books in this library. ...Er, right?
Guys, we can't read all these books!\nIt's gonna take foreeeeeever!
I'll let you in on a helpful little secret.\nWhen you SAY something's hard,\nit instantly gets much harder.
So instead, rear back your head and yell,\n＂I'M GONNA DOOF IT!＂
You are SO close to sounding cool\nmost of the time. But then...yeesh.
A-anyway, let's get our game faces on\nand start looking around.
Goodness, reading this many books is\njust as tiring as I expected it to be.
Dude, my poor faerie head is about to\nexplode into goo. I'm gonna take a break.
Go ahead if you like, Lathna.\nJust try to stay close.
C'mon, quit muttering and let's go!
Hoo doggie! That is one weird place,\neh, Lathna?
Wait, what? It's bad? What's that mean?!\nC'mon, you can't just say that and...
I heard somebody over there just now!\nThey were moaning, like, ＂Uuuuuurgh!＂
Notte, that's just a bookshelf.\nMaybe it's old and creaky or som—
I know what I heard, man!
Surely you aren't suggesting the BOOK\nwas talking? Because that is... It's...
This library has been sealed for ages,\nright? And yet, the books in this section\nlook to be in pristine condition.
Huh. You're right. They look brand new.\nI wonder what they're about...
There's nothing else written in it...\nWhat is the deal with this book...?
Look at this one, Your Highness.
STOP STOP STOP MAKE IT STOP MAKE IT STOP\nMAKE IT STOP MAKE IT STOP STOP STOP MAKE IT\nSTOP ME STOP ME STOP ME STOP ME STOP
...That goes on for hundreds of pages.
Is this a prank? Because I'm not laughing!
I wish that it were. I truly do.
I can't see even the most devoted\nprankster taking the time to fill all\nthe books in this area with gibberish.
Yeah, there must be a couple hundred\nof 'em in here.
We seek roughly 200 missing people,\nand here find roughly 200 new books.

More absurd than an entire village
disappearing in a single night?
Still, if you doubt my theory, we have
only to count the books and see.
All right, let me just do a quick count...\nLet's see... A hundred... One fifty...\nTwo hundred...and...eight? Oh no.
Which means we have the exact number\nof books as we have missing villagers.
Let us not get ahead of ourselves.\nWe have a theory right now, nothing more.
By Ilia, there are PEOPLE in these books!\nHow is such a thing possible?!
Okay, everybody just take a step back.\nIf the people have become books,\nthen the books are still people!
Why can't ANYONE make sense today?!

I think what Curran is trying to say is
that if the people became books, they
should also be able to turn BACK into
people. ...Er, is that right?
That's my guess, anyway.\nWhat do you think, Heinwald?
The remaining grimoire... A spell...\nA new world...offering...failed.\nNo, it succeeded? Ah! How fascinating!
HEY! Heinwald! This isn't the time to\nbe squirreled away off in your own little\nworld. We need to do something, fast!
There is nothing we can do presently.\nOur only choice is to widen our\ninvestigative radius a bit more.
And how do we do that?

The seals placed on this library are
multifarious. If we release those seals,
the range of what we can investigate
will expand exponentially.
And how do we release these seals?
At the moment I am unsure; we need to\ngather clues in various areas of the library.
Well, I guess that's better than being\nburied up to my neck in creepy books.\nSo sure—count me in on the clue hunt.
I thought you might say that.\nWhat say you, {player_name}?
We'll go as well. If the villagers really\ndid get turned into books, we can't leave\nthem trapped in that state.
It's funny. Life's too long to spend it\nstanding around idly, but it's too shirt\nto do all the things that matter.
